<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-435  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 435.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Sept 1990 v7 n9 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>COCOM spurs export reforms: networking software, equipmentexperience most dramatic decontrol.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>St. Clair, Melanie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls(COCOM), spurred by the Bush administration, is responding to thegeneral easing of relations between East and West by acorresponding relaxation of the rules governing export of computerhardware and software products to the Soviet Union and its allies.andO;A high-level COCOM meeting took place in Paris, France in earlyJun 1990; the interim changes decided upon at the meeting tookeffect on Jul 1.andP;  More meetings will be held during the balance of1990.andP;  COCOM, comprised of 17 nations, will now work from a'positive' list; items not included on the list will be consideredclear for export.andP;  The US also has specific levels of control forvarious countries, with some, including North Korea and Vietnam,being denied exports of any type, technological or otherwise.andP;  Themost significant changes among the COCOM controls are the movementof East Germany to the same level of trade as West Germany, andthe institution of General License GCT, a regulation that willremove the requirement for exporters to obtain individual exportlicenses for certain widely traded items.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeExportCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>